Yes, Tauri works perfectly on PC (Windows). In fact, delivering lightweight Windows applications is one of the framework's biggest strengths.
Here is how Tauri handles Windows compared to what you experienced on Mac:
## The Rendering Engine
On your Mac, Tauri relies on Apple's WKWebView to render your app's frontend. On Windows, it uses **Microsoft Edge WebView2**.
Because WebView2 is built directly into Windows 10 and 11, your application doesn't need to bundle a browser like Electron does. This means your Windows executable (.exe or .msi) will be incredibly small — often between 3MB and 8MB — and will use a fraction of the RAM.
## Building for Windows
Your frontend code, your Rust backend, and your SQLite database will generally work exactly the same on Windows. However, because Tauri relies heavily on native OS toolchains, cross-compiling a Windows app directly from a Mac is quite difficult.
To actually generate the Windows installer for your app, you have two main options:
 1. **Use a Windows Machine:** You can clone your repository onto a PC, install the Microsoft C++ Build Tools and the Windows Rust toolchain (x86_64-pc-windows-msvc), and run tauri build.
 2. **Use GitHub Actions:** This is the most common approach for Mac developers. You can set up a CI/CD pipeline using the official tauri-action. When you push your code to GitHub, it automatically spins up a temporary Windows server in the cloud, compiles your code into an .msi installer, and attaches it to a release.


Setting up a GitHub Action is the perfect workaround for compiling a Windows app from a Mac. It offloads the heavy lifting to Microsoft's cloud infrastructure.
Here is a step-by-step guide to creating an automated pipeline that will build your Windows executable (.exe and .msi) every time you push your code.
### Step 1: Create the Workflow File
In the root directory of your Tauri project on your Mac, you need to create a specific folder structure that GitHub recognizes.
 1. Create a folder named .github (notice the dot at the beginning).
 2. Inside that, create a folder named workflows.
 3. Inside workflows, create a file named windows-build.yml.
### Step 2: Add the Configuration Code
Open the windows-build.yml file and paste the following configuration. This script tells GitHub to spin up a Windows machine, install Node.js and Rust, build your frontend, and then compile your Tauri app.
```yaml
name: Build Windows App

# This tells GitHub to run the action whenever you push to the 'main' branch
on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build-windows:
    runs-on: windows-latest

    steps:
      - name: Checkout repository
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Setup Node.js
        uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with:
          node-version: 20

      - name: Install Rust toolchain
        uses: dtolnay/rust-toolchain@stable
        with:
          targets: x86_64-pc-windows-msvc

      - name: Install frontend dependencies
        # Change 'npm install' to 'yarn install' or 'pnpm install' if you use those
        run: npm install

      - name: Build and bundle Tauri app
        uses: tauri-apps/tauri-action@v0
        env:
          # This token is automatically provided by GitHub Actions
          GITHUB_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
        with:
          # This creates a draft release on GitHub with your installer attached
          tagName: v__VERSION__
          releaseName: 'App v__VERSION__'
          releaseBody: 'Automated Windows Build'
          releaseDraft: true
          prerelease: false

```
### Step 3: Grant Permissions (If necessary)
Because this action creates a "Release" on your GitHub repository to host the installer files, GitHub Actions needs permission to write to your repo.
 1. Go to your repository on GitHub.com.
 2. Click **Settings** > **Actions** > **General**.
 3. Scroll down to **Workflow permissions**.
 4. Ensure **"Read and write permissions"** is selected and save.
### Step 4: Push to GitHub
Now, simply commit your new workflow file and push it to your repository:
```bash
git add .github/workflows/windows-build.yml
git commit -m "Add Windows build action"
git push origin main

```
### Step 5: Download your Windows App
Once you push, GitHub will automatically start the build process.
 1. Go to your repository on GitHub.com.
 2. Click the **Actions** tab at the top. You will see your "Build Windows App" workflow running. (Note: Rust compilation takes a few minutes, so this usually takes about 10-15 minutes to finish).
 3. Once the workflow turns green (completed), click on the **Releases** section on the right side of your repository's main page.
 4. You will see a new **Draft Release**. Inside its "Assets" section, you will find your compiled .msi (installer) and .exe files!
You can now send that .msi file to any Windows user, and they can install your app natively.
